Problem:
Given an incomplete Sudoku in the form of matrix mat[][] of order 9*9, the task is to solve the Sudoku. It is guaranteed that the input Sudoku will have exactly one solution.

A sudoku solution must satisfy all of the following rules:

Each of the digits 1-9 must occur exactly once in each row.
Each of the digits 1-9 must occur exactly once in each column.
Each of the digits 1-9 must occur exactly once in each of the 9, 3x3 sub-boxes of the grid.
Note: Zeros represent blanks to be filled with numbers 1-9, while non-zero cells are fixed and cannot be changed.


Time complexity: O(9^81)
Space complexity: O(9*9) -> Stack space

Code:
class Solution {
    public void solveSudoku(int[][] mat) {
        solve(mat);    
    }

    private boolean solve(int[][] mat) {  
        for(int row = 0; row < 9; row++) {
            for(int col = 0; col < 9; col++) {
                
                if(mat[row][col] == 0) {
                    
                    for(int k = 1; k <= 9; k++) {
                        if(isValid(row, col, k, mat)) {
                            mat[row][col] = k;
                            if(solve(mat)) return true;
                            mat[row][col] = 0;
                        }
                    }
                    
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }
        
        return true;
        
    }
    
    
    private boolean isValid(int row, int col, int value, int[][] mat) {
 
        for(int i = 0; i < 9; i++) {
            
            if(mat[i][col] == value) return false;
            if(mat[row][i] == value) return false;
            
            if(mat[(row/3)*3 + (i/3)][(col/3) * 3 + (i%3)] == value) return false;
            
        }
        
        return true;
        
    }
}